<font color="#FF0000">VARIOUS &amp; SUNDRY POINTS</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jun 30  1:30:07 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Off Line for a week and this site explodes.<br><br>
1. To Cook: As a guy who served several stints as a perimeter duty officer; I know the rules of engagement well, and I don't believe they were different for the Marines than for the Army.  Unless you had people getting into the wire, NOBODY was to open fire WITHOUT CLEARANCE.  I spent 45 minutes with my heels locked at attention with a colonel in my face, largely due to a fed up rifle company, just back from 2 fruitless weeks humping in the boonies, that opened up with every thing but the kitchen sink after receiving a few desultory rounds.  Didn't get the snipers on the far hill, but sure tore up the village in between; which was what the VC wanted, and had a propaganda field day with.  As for opening up only 5 minutes past curfew; that's bullshit, and you should know it, and that's even with accepting your points on people out late where they should not be. <br><br>
2. Yes, Ho Chi Minh was a nationalist first, but he became a Communist early, and was one of the founding members of the French Communist Party, and that was before Versailles.<br><br>
3. The AK-47 dates to 1943 - definately a WWII weapon.<br><br>
4. While 939 may be the independence date, it took 400 more years before repeated attempts at reconquest by China ceased.  At which point the Vietnamese turned aggressors themselves and displaced the Khmers (Cambodians) from all of the country south of the Binh Dinh/Quang Ngai border. [There is the ruin of an old Khmer temple outside of Qui Nhon near the junction of Routes 1 &amp; 19 that the Korean Tiger Division used as a radio tower].  The Cambodians have never completely forgiven the Vietnamese for taking the Mekong Delta.<br><br>
5. For the 4th time in these posts; it was known in my intelligence company that, at least in Binh Dinh province as late as summer 1968, Ho Chi Minh would win any election with his name on the ballot.  The &quot;free&quot; elections of carried only those candidates that the government did not deem subversive.  South Vietnam was an artificial creation that never fully developed a sense of itself beyond the negative of being anti-Communist.  I still get furious over the venality and corruption that affected the average Vietnamese day in and day out.  The phrase goes, &quot;You can't beat somebody with nobody.&quot;  The South Vietnamese government existed in an ever growing political, cultural and moral vacuum.  We could have beat the NVA upside down and sideways to hell and back and still not been able to put Humpty Dumpty together so that a peace could be won.  Taking Hanoi wouldn't have been any more effective than Napolean taking Moscow.<br><br>
6. Diem &amp; Co were largely displaced NORTHERN Catholics.  Granted they had good reason for not wanting Communist rule, but many were no more native to the South than Ho's sleepers.<br><br>
7. Yes, the North Vietnamese were duplicitous about the Geneva accords.  Not that it excuses them, but if we were in their shoes; I doubt if we would have done any different, with a treaty literally shoved down our throats.  A good example of a similar agreement is the one that partitioned Ireland, got Michael Collins assassinated, and still produces a steady flow of blood 75 years later.<br><br>
8. As someone pointed out elsewhere on site, &quot;that no one was seen walking North.&quot;  The converse is that the North's Armies didn't collapse when hit hard with great casualties, like during the 1972 Easter offensive.  I doubt if 10% of the rank and file were die hard Communist Party members.<br><br>
9. We meant well, and to do right.  But as they say, the road to hell.....  <br><br>

<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


